"Be pleased, my lord, to accept with your wontesd goodness this unworthy present which I make you. T have taken off one trouble from you, of defending it, by acknowledging its imperfections : and though some part of them are covered in the verse (as Erichthonius rode always in a chariot, to hide his lameness), such of them as cannot be concealed, you will please to connive at, though, in the strict- ness of your judgment, you cannot pardon. If Homer was allowed to nod sometimes in so longa work, it will be no wonder if I often fall- asleep. You tock my Aureng-zebe into your protection,"